Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper proposes a new class of nonbinary polar codes for ultra-reliable and low-latency communications (URLLC) and discusses the bit-level code construction and modulation schemes to support high spectral efficiency. This falls under the scope of information theory.
2. cs.COMM (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper discusses the application of the proposed nonbinary polar codes for 5G URLLC, which is a topic related to networking and internet architecture.
3. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper proposes a new coding scheme for communication systems, which can be considered as a topic related to systems and control.
4. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - Although the paper does not explicitly discuss cryptography and security, the proposed codes can potentially be used for secure communication, which falls under the scope of cryptography and security.
5. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper does not focus on data structures and algorithms, but the discussion on the encoder/decoder structure and implementation can be considered as a topic related to data structures and algorithms.
